In <3nh8j7$eho@post.gsfc.nasa.gov>, johnl@medusa.gsfc.nasa.gov (OS2 User) writes:
>Markus Kuhn (mskuhn@cip.informatik.uni-erlangen.de) wrote:
>: Most modern boards do not support parity bits any more. In the past few
>: years, improved RAM production processes have increased the reliability
>: of RAM so dramatically that it is very unlikely that you will experience any
>: parity error detection in the first 10 years of operation of your
>: PC.
>
>Then why do I keep on running into bad SIMMs? I follow ESD procedures
>and I still get bad SIMMs, mostly with hard to find pattern sensitivity
>problems. Intel doesn't care if floating point results are correct and
>evidently they don't care if the DRAM works. I could understand dropping
>parity if all SIMMs were qualified and properly tested for the motherboard
>they were installed in. In the real world this rarely happens. The last set
>of SIMMs I installed (4 4Mx9) had two bad SIMMs. They passed the power
>up self test but would fail after several hours/days of use. The brain dead
>PC hardware design doesn't latch the address of a parity error so it took
>several weeks to isolate the problem.
>
>Most PC vendors seem to think that their profit margins are much
>more important than the integrity of their customer's data.

Quality is the first area to suffer when price is the factor upon which buying
decisions are made.  We have not seen a bad SIMM in a very long time, but we
pay more for the highest quality memory.  I see no reason to use x36 SIMMs that
have parity when Apples have never used parity, and the entire list of "tier one"
names do not use x36 72 pin SIMMs.  Considering our memory supplier also produces
a very expensive memory test unit, and it is used as final QC on thier production
line, it's easy to understand my confidence, that and they are located a few miles
from our facility, so I've been inside their operations 100's of times to verify the
quality control procedures.....


